GETS GO-AHEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF KASS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A memorial to two police officers killed last February by an attempted robber 
during a management seminar has been approved by the Palos Verdes Estates Art 
Jury, ending a months of wrangling.  
</P>
<P>
 The Art Jury, a private organization that reviews city building plans, 
approved the memorial Monday under the condition that two walking paths be 
removed and a sundial be lowered from 12 to 11 feet, said Philip J. Frengs, 
chairman of the memorial committee. 
</P>
<P>
 The memorial, which will also honor war veterans, will be located in a park 
across from City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council approved the memorial in August, but the Art Jury rejected 
the original plans in September after residents complained that it was too 
elaborate.  
</P>
<P>
 Memorial supporters, who have raised $10,000, must raise an additional 
$90,000. Originally, the memorial was estimated to cost about $226,000. 
</P>
<P>
 Frengs said he hoped the approval will aid fund-raising efforts. JEFF KASS 
