<HEADLINE>
<P>
SWEET AND SOUR 'JELLY'; BECAUSE OF NEGATIVE FEELINGS FOR MORTON, MAURICE HINES 
HAD TROUBLE GETTING INTO THE ROLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS PASLES, Chris Pasles covers classical music and dance for The Times 
Orange County Edition. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "Jelly's Last Jam" has plenty of songs and dances, but it isn't your usual 
Broadway musical. It's a musical with a mission, and a controversial one at 
that: To put jazz creator Jelly Roll Morton on trial as a bigot for denying his 
own black heritage. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's a monster," says Maurice Hines, who plays Jelly in the touring 
production, beginning Tuesday at the Orange County Performing Arts Center in 
Costa Mesa. "Black, white, Asian -- anybody who denies his own race and takes 
from them, I will always think of as a monster." 
</P>
<P>
 George C. Wolfe wrote (and directs) the show to tell the story of Morton on 
his last day on Earth, as he stands on the brink of heaven or hell and reflects 
on his life. Wolfe's portrait of Morton is mostly an unflattering one, but the 
musical ends happily, with Morton redeemed and taken into the pantheon of great 
black American creators. 
</P>
<P>
 "In real life," counters Hines, "he didn't redeem himself. But we live in 
America, and they love happy endings." 
</P>
<P>
 Born Ferdinand Le Menthe Morton about 1890 in New Orleans (there are other 
ways of spelling his name and other dates for his birth year), he rose to fame 
playing music based on the rhythms and sounds he heard on the streets and in 
the brothels as a youngster. His great-grandmother had kicked him out of the 
house when he was 15 for hanging around such places and people, or "lower 
orders" as she called them. 
</P>
<P>
 He left New Orleans in 1915 and formed his own band, the Red Hot Peppers, in 
Chicago. The band became one of the top black recording groups for RCA Records. 
Calling himself "Jelly Roll" (to suggest sexiness) and flush with success, he 
started living a flashier life, bought lots of suits and had a small diamond 
inserted into a front tooth. 
</P>
<P>
 But by 1930, when he moved to New York, his music began to go out of fashion 
as a new kind of big band sound became popular. His career went into decline, 
and, after years of neglecting his health, he died, broke and largely 
forgotten, in the colored ward of the Los Angeles Hospital in 1941. To the end, 
he professed to be superior to black Americans, saying he was pure Creole. 
</P>
<P>
 "Jelly's Last Jam" was first produced in Los Angeles in 1991 at the Mark Taper 
Forum. Its eight-week run broke all box office records for such engagements. 
</P>
<P>
 Although Gregory Hines, Maurice's younger brother, had been slated to star in 
the original production, he bowed out because of a conflict with a movie 
project that, ironically, never materialized. Morton was played in Los Angeles 
by Obba Babatunde. 
</P>
<P>
 But Gregory Hines took over when, after some minor tinkering, the musical 
moved to Broadway in 1992. There, the show played for 569 performances and 
gathered 11 Tony nominations. The production hit the road for the first time in 
September, with Maurice Hines as Jelly. The music is by Morton and Luther 
Henderson; the lyrics are by Susan Birkenhead. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite his negative feelings, Maurice Hines, 50, admits that Morton is 
"certainly three-dimensional. He's got a lot of layers to him." And the musical 
does "show how he became the person he did through his family problems. There 
was racism in his own light-skinned family. It was that Creole way of life in 
New Orleans." 
</P>
<P>
 But he disagrees with those who call Morton a genius. "I think he was 
innovative, I think that he was creative, but I think his own egomania stopped 
the creativity when it should have grown," he says. 
</P>
<P>
 "Duke (Ellington), Ella (Fitzgerald), Lionel Hampton, Cab Calloway -- they 
really nurtured each other, they loved each other. There was never a 
competition among them, as far as I see or knew. But there was with Jelly Roll, 
because of this race problem, and his egomania killed him." 
</P>
<P>
 As for airing such intra-racial strife, Hines isn't convinced it's necessary. 
His producer, he says, thinks it's "such an important thing to do." 
</P>
<P>
 "Important for whom? As black people, we know (bigotry) exists in our race. Is 
it important for white people to know? I don't consider myself controversial. I 
think I'm politically aware. But I don't think it's that important to put it 
out for other people to see. We already know about it as black people." 
</P>
<P>
 Even so, Hines has his own understanding of the problem. His mother, Alma 
Hines Kilfoyl, now 75, also came from a light-skinned family, and when she 
married a darker-skinned man, Maurice Sr., her family looked down on him. 
</P>
<P>
 "My family certainly knew that attitude between the 'good' hair and the 'bad' 
hair, the 'white' and the 'black,' " he says. "But my mother put a stop to that 
immediately. She was light enough to pass (for white) but didn't. She never 
allowed things of that nature in the house. 
</P>
<P>
 "So it was not difficult to get into that kind of part and bring truth to it. 
It's easy. The rage is also easy to touch." 
</P>
<P>
 In fact, Hines took over the role because his mother asked him to. "My mother 
knew I really didn't want to do it," he says. "But you know how mothers can 
give you that killing look, like 'Do this for me.' So I said finally, 'OK. I 
will.' " 
</P>
<P>
 His mother is so important to him that he dedicates all his performances to 
her (and to his manager, Stanley Kay). "My mother is one of the great ladies of 
my life," he says. "She wasn't a mother in name only. She said, 'What makes my 
sons happy, makes me happy.' She proved to us that she meant what she said. My 
brother and I have taken her to the mountaintop many a time, believe me. She 
held the family together when my father wasn't working. There are lots of stuff 
we remember." 
</P>
<P>
 He remembers that he and his brother, who is two years younger, began dancing 
as children, first as the Hines Kids and later the Hines Brothers. In 1962, 
Maurice Sr. joined the duo as a drummer and the act became Hines, Hines and 
Dad. 
</P>
<P>
 Six years later, however, Gregory Hines left to strike out on his own. The 
brothers had had a history of quarreling and Gregory's departure further 
chilled their relationship. After Francis Ford Coppola learned about their 
feelings, he made use of the conflict when he featured both brothers in his 
1984 film "The Cotton Club." 
</P>
<P>
 Gregory Hines, in an interview published in 1992, said that he and his brother 
hadn't spoken to each other for the past six years. Maurice, however, refuses 
to discuss the matter in the press. "My brother sees fit to talk about it," he 
says. "I never talk about my personal life with strangers." 
</P>
<P>
 So how does he feel about taking over his brother's role? First, he points out 
that Gregory was the second Morton, not the first, taking over for Babatunde. 
</P>
<P>
 Second, he's "completely re-choreographed" his dances, and even suggested 
dropping out of a second-act duet with 21-year-old Savion Glover, who plays 
Morton as a young man, because "Savion is now an acknowledged tap star. He 
should have his moment alone on the stage." 
</P>
<P>
 Further, Maurice never saw the show, either on Broadway or in Los Angeles, 
where he lives. "I came as a clean canvas," he says. "In that way, it helped 
(director Wolfe) look at things and think what could have been done better, 
differently. It's always a work in progress." 
</P>
<P>
 Differences? "I cry a lot sooner, I am more tormented." 
</P>
<P>
 Moreover, "My brother and I tap completely differently although we were both 
taught by Henry LeTang. We have very different stances. My style tries to be 
exactly like Fayard Nicholas, a full body style. (Gregory) dances from the 
waist down, like Harold (Nicholas). I'm more pulled up. We are so different. No 
one has really compared us." 
</P>
<P>
 Besides Fayard Nicholas, the dancer who really inspired him, he says, was 
Teddy Hale, a great black rhythm tapper who died before he became widely known. 
</P>
<P>
 "My style is a combination of Teddy Hale and Fayard," he says. "I don't get a 
chance to do it that much, because of the syncopation. But my style comes 
through every now and then." 
</P>
<P>
 One problem, he says, is that Morton was a pianist, not a dancer. "So what I 
do when I dance is sort of play the piano at the same time. I throw the steps 
as if I'm playing the piano. It works because the man supposedly -- he did, but 
he wasn't the only one -- invented syncopation. Tap is really a percussion 
instrument -- it's not tied to anything melodic. You can use different forms of 
syncopation tap-wise to portray the music rhythmically. So I think, used 
metaphorically, it works exceptionally well." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, because of his negative feelings about Morton, he says he had 
difficulties getting into the role. "I finally got into the pocket of the show 
in the third performances in New Orleans. I felt I was really being truthful. I 
hit it. The whole cast knew it." 
</P>
<P>
 What had happened? "The creative process is so mystical," he says, "you don't 
even know where it comes from. When you hit it, it's just there. I don't 
over-analyze anything. I just go with it. Otherwise it becomes mechanical. I 
don't want it to be a trick. I want it to be real." 
</P>
<P>
 * THEATER LISTINGS, Page 24 
</P>
<P>
 What: Maurice Hines in "Jelly's Last Jam." (Also starring Savion Glover.) 
</P>
<P>
 When: Tuesday, Nov. 29, through Dec. 2 at 8 p.m.; Dec. 3 at 2 and 8 p.m.; Dec. 
4 at 2 and 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Where: The Orange County Performing Arts Center, 600 Town Center Drive, Costa 
Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
 Whereabouts: San Diego (405) Freeway to Bristol Street north exit. Proceed on 
Bristol, then turn right on Town Center Drive. 
</P>
