<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE BASKETBALL: 1994-95 PREVIEW; CAL STATE FULLERTON; INTERIM COACH LIKELY 
TO FACE A TOUGH YEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LON EUBANKS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Brad Holland had trouble seeing a light at the end of the tunnel at Cal State 
Fullerton after two seasons as basketball coach. So when the University of San 
Diego job opened in September, Holland grabbed his bags, which some suspect he 
had never unpacked, and was on his way.  
</P>
<P>
 That left the job to his top assistant, Bob Hawking, hired on an interim basis 
by new Athletic Director John Easterbrook, who walked in the same day Holland 
walked out. 
</P>
<P>
 And now Hawking finds himself peering into that same dark tunnel, perhaps 
wondering if there's anything in there other than an onrushing locomotive. 
</P>
<P>
 "I guess every basketball magazine around has picked us to finish last in the 
Big West Conference, so we know we're going to have a challenge ahead of us," 
Hawking said. The Titans also were picked to finish last by both conference 
coaches and reporters in separate preseason polls. 
</P>
<P>
 Challenge, for certain. 
</P>
<P>
 Hawking was Don MacLean's coach in high school at Simi Valley, but he doesn't 
have anyone of MacLean's ability to build a team around this year at Fullerton. 
</P>
<P>
 And the players who do return are from a team that was 8-19, the school's 
worst record since the Titans won only four games in the 1981-82 season. 
</P>
<P>
 Fullerton's best player is senior Winston Peterson, a 6-foot-6, 235-pound 
center. He led the team in scoring, rebounding and shooting last season. 
Peterson averaged 15.3 points, 7.5 rebounds and shot 53.7% from the field. Not 
bad, although Hawking says he has high expectations for Peterson this season. 
</P>
<P>
 Fullerton's third-leading scorer last season, forward Darren Little, stumbled 
academically in the spring and was not readmitted in the fall. He averaged 11.7 
points and was third on the team in rebounding. And forward Josh King, who 
showed promise as a freshman, transferred to Rhode Island.  
</P>
<P>
 Another returning starter, guard James French, a transfer from Washington who 
averaged 9.1 points last season, will be a key player as Hawking tries to speed 
up the offense. French has quickness and his success igniting the fast break 
could be telling. 
</P>
<P>
 More turnovers have followed the faster pace in the preseason.  
</P>
<P>
 "To some degree, that goes with developing more of an up-tempo game," Hawking 
said.  
</P>
<P>
 Hawking hopes the other returning regular, wiry forward David Frigout, will be 
significantly improved over his first year in American college basketball after 
transferring from Groupe Pigier University in Evreux, France, last year. The 
more physical American game made for a difficult adjustment, and he still has 
problems defensively against forwards who play with power. Frigout has been 
prone to fouling.  
</P>
<P>
 What has pleased Hawking is the greater depth the team has shown. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've had some really intense battles for the starting positions," Hawking 
said. "And I think we're going to be playing eight to 10 guys on a fairly 
regular basis." 
</P>
<P>
 It's likely the Titans will have three guards in the lineup at times as 
Hawking emphasizes the faster pace. Chuck Overton, a first team All-American at 
Salt Lake City Community College last season, already has shown he can help. 
Junior Ali Nayab, sophomore Chris St. Clair and redshirt freshman Chris Dade 
also figure into the mix at guard. So will senior Danny Robinson if he regains 
academic eligibility at the start of the new semester.  
</P>
<P>
 Senior Fred Amos and redshirt freshman DeVaughn Wright are the other inside 
players who will play.  
</P>
<P>
 Hawking has been particularly pleased with the play of Amos, who has been 
challenging Peterson for the center spot. 
</P>
<P>
 Hawking just shrugs off the negative karma that swirls around the Titans. 
</P>
<P>
 The dire predictions don't seem to unsettle him as the season opener Tuesday 
against Cal State Northridge, his alma mater, nears.  
</P>
<P>
 By March, however, Hawking could either be riding that train out of the 
tunnel, or just be another Fullerton coach run over by it. Fullerton Facts and 
Figures 
</P>
<P>
